summary: I don't know how to link posts on mobile but @lieutenant-sapphic just brought up the nightingale again and it's got me, it's...
body:
I don’t know how to link posts on mobile but @lieutenant-sapphic just brought up the nightingale again and it’s got me, it’s just GOT me because

it’s the end of the book. it’s the very last we ever see of them, and there they are together and the nightingale starts to sing for the first. time. ever.

That feels so significant to me? They’ve been dining at the Ritz many times before, but now, only now, after all they’ve just been through together, after everything is somehow the same but still also somehow different… now the nightingale is there, singing. (Nobody hears it (yet?). But it’s there all the same.)

That speaks to me of change. These two, who i really think have had roughly the same sort of relationship for millennia; with literal eternity before them, with no cause to really rush, change, grow - they have changed now. And this, this is after. And ringing in this after, and all the rest of their future to come, quiet and yet unheard but there…

…is the freaking Nightingale and the song lyrics that go with it and WHO THOUGHT OF THIS I JUST WANT TO TALK I HAVE QUESTIONS

summary: Do you know just how many times Crowley and Aziraphale call each other “angel” and “dear” in canon? I tried counting during my...
question: Do you know just how many times Crowley and Aziraphale call each other “angel” and “dear” in canon? I tried counting during my last reread (saturday) but I feel like I lost count bc it didn’t seem like very many times at all…
answer:
Hi there, anon!  As it happens, I do know the answer off the top of my head:

Aziraphale calls Crowley my dear once and my dear boy once as well.  Never just dear; it always has my before it and / or boy following.  Each example, I think, is taken as blanket evidence that these are things Aziraphale must call Crowley reasonably often, as comfortably as he uses them.

Crowley calls Aziraphale angel twice.  The same representative casual, comfortable use applies.  The parallelism is lovely; they each call each other by their endearments for each other the same number of times.

summary: probably you've posted about this before but can you like. explain the nightingale to me
question: probably you've posted about this before but can you like. explain the nightingale to me
answer:
THE NIGHITNGALE HTE N GI U GHING  GAL E THE NIGHTINGALE okay

That certain night
The night we met
There was magic abroad in the air
There were angels dining at the Ritz
And a nightingale sang in Berkeley square
I may be right; I may be wrong
But I’m perfectly willing to swear
That when you turned and smiled at me
A nightingale sang in Berkeley square.
The moon that lingered over London town
Poor puzzled moon; he wore a frown
How could he know we two were so in love
The whole damned world seemed upside down
The streets of town were paved with stars
It was such a romantic affair
And as we kissed and said goodnight
A nightingale sang in Berkeley square.

every time i think about it i die

summary: London was not designed for cars. Come to that, it wasn’t designed for people. It just sort of happened. This created problems,...
body:
London was not designed for cars. Come to that, it wasn’t designed for people. It just sort of happened. This created problems, and the solutions that were implemented became the next problems, five or ten or a hundred years down the line.

 - Neil Gaiman and Terry Pratchett, Good Omens

summary: I love the fact that how you level up (geeks don’t age, they level up) and learn new things, it enables you enjoy previously...
body:
I love the fact that how you level up (geeks don’t age, they level up) and learn new things, it enables you enjoy previously unknown references in books such as Good Omens.

For example for my first three readings of Good Omens I didn’t watch Doctor Who, so the part: 

Brilliant blue light shone out, outlining three alien shapes. They walked down the ramp. At least, two of them walked. The one that looked like a pepper pot just skidded down it, and fell over at the bottom.

was nice but I didn’t understand the reference. And in my fourth reading I was: Oh! A dalek! :)))

(And I really wish we will see the poor falling dalek in the show.)
